The cultural layer (this is where it gets really interesting)

4. Myth-making in modern form

Wrestlers are modern mythological characters:
	•	Dwayne Johnson → charismatic demigod / trickster king
	•	Stone Cold Steve Austin → anti-authority rebel
	•	John Cena → virtuous warrior / incorruptible hero
	•	The Undertaker → death archetype

These aren’t just personas—they’re compressed cultural narratives.

Wrestling functions like:
	•	Greek myths
	•	Shakespeare plays
	•	comic books

…but performed through bodies instead of text.

⸻

5. Kayfabe: the “agreed illusion”

Historically, wrestling protected the illusion that it was real. This is called kayfabe.

Even today:
	•	everyone knows it’s scripted
	•	but everyone plays along anyway

It’s a shared contract between performer and audience:

“We know it’s not real—but we will feel it as if it is.”

That’s actually a very advanced cultural behavior.

⸻

6. Improvisation under constraint

Matches are often:
	•	partially scripted (who wins, big moments)
	•	partially improvised (timing, pacing, recovery)

Wrestlers communicate mid-match through:
	•	subtle cues
	•	body pressure
	•	eye contact

It’s like:

jazz + stunt work + acting
all happening simultaneously

⸻

7. Evolution across cultures

Wrestling isn’t just WWE—it’s global, and each culture shapes it differently:
	•	Japan (Puroresu) → more “sport-like,” harder hitting, honor-based
	•	Mexico (Lucha Libre) → faster, acrobatic, mask mythology
	•	US (WWE style) → character-driven, narrative-heavy

Each version emphasizes a different axis:
	•	realism
	•	spectacle
	•	storytelling

